1
00:00:02,836 --> 00:00:06,335
"When I have fears
that I may cease to be,

2
00:00:06,336 --> 00:00:10,334
"before my pen
has gleamed my teaming brain,

3
00:00:10,335 --> 00:00:13,751
"before high-piled books
and charactery

4
00:00:13,752 --> 00:00:18,418
"hold like rich garners
a full ripened brain.

5
00:00:18,419 --> 00:00:22,000
"When I behold upon
the night’s stark face,

6
00:00:22,001 --> 00:00:26,043
"huge cloudy symbols
of a high romance

7
00:00:26,044 --> 00:00:31,083
"and think that I may never
live to trace their shadows

8
00:00:31,084 --> 00:00:33,377
"with the magic hand
of chance.

9
00:00:35,168 --> 00:00:40,459
"And when I feel fair
creature of an hour,

10
00:00:40,460 --> 00:00:43,916
"that I shall never
look upon thee more.

11
00:00:43,917 --> 00:00:46,166
"Never have relish
the fairy power

12
00:00:46,167 --> 00:00:48,168
"of unreflected love.

13
00:00:50,377 --> 00:00:53,708
"Then on the shore
on the wide world

14
00:00:53,709 --> 00:00:56,083
"I stand alone.

15
00:00:56,084 --> 00:00:58,750
"To think, to love,

16
00:00:58,751 --> 00:01:02,709
and fame to
nothingness to sink."

17
00:01:09,417 --> 00:01:11,917
WOMAN [LAUGHS]: Oh!
Oh, nice.

18
00:01:11,918 --> 00:01:13,999
You’re gonna be
a ravishing bride, Fran.

19
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:15,915
Let me guess.

20
00:01:15,916 --> 00:01:17,875
Diane!

21
00:01:17,876 --> 00:01:19,665
They’ll go great
with that red dress

22
00:01:19,666 --> 00:01:22,082
you’re getting married in.
Oh, no.

23
00:01:22,083 --> 00:01:24,999
Not me. I want
every ounce of tradition.

24
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,666
Marching down that aisle.

25
00:01:26,667 --> 00:01:29,915
Everyone gasping,
"isn’t she spectacular?"

26
00:01:29,916 --> 00:01:32,874
And then Mark lifts my veil,

27
00:01:32,875 --> 00:01:37,123
and he gazes into my eyes
for a long moment.

28
00:01:37,124 --> 00:01:38,748
It better be long.
DIANE: Mmm.

29
00:01:38,749 --> 00:01:40,957
I’ve dreamt about it
ever since I was a child.

30
00:01:40,958 --> 00:01:43,540
Oh, yes.
And then the nightmare begins.

31
00:01:43,541 --> 00:01:45,957
Oh, Nancy.
Don’t listen to her.

32
00:01:45,958 --> 00:01:47,248
Marriage is beautiful.

33
00:01:47,249 --> 00:01:49,290
Keeps the dew fresh
on your eyelids.

34
00:01:49,291 --> 00:01:52,665
Maggie teaches poetry,
she doesn’t write it.

35
00:01:52,666 --> 00:01:54,957
Marriage gives you
a point of view of balance.

36
00:01:54,958 --> 00:01:57,499
The lens you see things
through that’s important.

37
00:01:57,500 --> 00:02:00,124
Well, I’ve had a problem
with 20-20 vision

38
00:02:00,125 --> 00:02:02,165
with both
of my husbands.

39
00:02:02,166 --> 00:02:04,915
Hey, this is a bridal shower,
not group therapy.

40
00:02:04,916 --> 00:02:06,581
Just one bit of advice, Fran.

41
00:02:06,582 --> 00:02:09,122
IN UNISON: Oh, no!
Oh, no. This is vital.

42
00:02:09,123 --> 00:02:11,497
Whatever you do,
have your own bathroom.

43
00:02:11,498 --> 00:02:14,956
I mean, there are some things
you just don’t wanna see him do.

44
00:02:14,957 --> 00:02:16,789
Ugh.

45
00:02:16,790 --> 00:02:19,498
A toast, to Fran.

46
00:02:19,499 --> 00:02:21,914
FRAN: Mm, okay.
Yes.

47
00:02:21,915 --> 00:02:23,831
[MAGGIE SIGHS]

48
00:02:23,832 --> 00:02:25,497
Happiness forever.

49
00:02:25,498 --> 00:02:27,665
MAGGIE:
To a man who’s your soul mate.

50
00:02:27,666 --> 00:02:30,581
Fresh dew on your eyelids.
Hmm.

51
00:02:30,582 --> 00:02:33,413
BOTH:
And your own bathroom.

52
00:02:34,414 --> 00:02:36,497
Oh.
Oh.

53
00:02:36,498 --> 00:02:38,830
Oh, I’m sorry. Oh, God.
NANCY: Here, here.

54
00:02:38,831 --> 00:02:41,163
Oh, today of all days.
Here.

55
00:02:41,164 --> 00:02:42,371
Oh.

56
00:02:42,372 --> 00:02:44,164
FRAN: Oh, here, here.
I’m sorry.

57
00:02:45,956 --> 00:02:48,162
Mom, hey, Mom. Wait up.

58
00:02:48,163 --> 00:02:49,247
Can I borrow the car?

59
00:02:49,248 --> 00:02:50,663
Oh, sorry.

60
00:02:50,664 --> 00:02:53,079
Home to change.
Betrayed again by chocolate.

61
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:54,788
You look fine.
I do not look fine.

62
00:02:54,789 --> 00:02:56,955
I have a meeting
with curriculum committee

63
00:02:56,956 --> 00:02:59,329
in, uh,
47 minutes.

64
00:02:59,330 --> 00:03:01,579
I’m not gonna give them
the chance to say no.

65
00:03:01,580 --> 00:03:03,247
Now where are my keys?

66
00:03:06,247 --> 00:03:08,370
Hey, do you have the list?

67
00:03:08,371 --> 00:03:10,830
Your anniversary party,
who you and Dad want to invite.

68
00:03:10,831 --> 00:03:12,870
Oh please, Diane, you don’t
need to give us a party.

69
00:03:12,871 --> 00:03:14,245
It’s just too expensive.

70
00:03:14,246 --> 00:03:15,662
Well,
why wait tables

71
00:03:15,663 --> 00:03:17,746
if I can’t squander
the money on my parents?

72
00:03:17,747 --> 00:03:19,704
Because you have student loans
and books.

73
00:03:19,705 --> 00:03:22,787
Mom, your 25th
anniversary is a major.

74
00:03:22,788 --> 00:03:24,912
How many of your friends
are you inviting?

75
00:03:24,913 --> 00:03:27,328
I wanna celebrate
you and Dad.

76
00:03:27,329 --> 00:03:30,037
Oh, listen,
your father and I

77
00:03:30,038 --> 00:03:33,120
are probably gonna go
to Bermuda, have a little sex.

78
00:03:33,121 --> 00:03:35,161
MAGGIE:
So touching.

79
00:03:35,162 --> 00:03:37,703
I think they’re
filthy perverts.

80
00:03:37,704 --> 00:03:38,911
When can I
have the car?

81
00:03:38,912 --> 00:03:40,786
Five o’clock.
Okay.

82
00:03:40,787 --> 00:03:43,203
Hey, and get that
list together!

83
00:03:43,204 --> 00:03:48,037
Key experience could be thought
of as intricate collages,

84
00:03:48,038 --> 00:03:52,036
crafted from
fragments of the past.

85
00:03:52,037 --> 00:03:55,453
But even more
relevant today.

86
00:03:55,454 --> 00:03:57,954
Particularly his view
of romantic love.

87
00:04:13,995 --> 00:04:16,952
[INAUDIBLE CHATTERING]

88
00:04:16,953 --> 00:04:18,453
[GASPS]

89
00:04:40,078 --> 00:04:42,078
[CAR DOORS CLOSE]

90
00:05:01,369 --> 00:05:03,576
TOM:
How’s that list
coming for Diane?

91
00:05:03,577 --> 00:05:05,699
She’s inviting everybody
we’ve ever met.

92
00:05:05,700 --> 00:05:07,659
Pretty impressive.

93
00:05:07,660 --> 00:05:09,367
Not too sure about
the Harrisons, though,

94
00:05:09,368 --> 00:05:11,867
he’s such a jerk.

95
00:05:11,868 --> 00:05:13,784
So how’s that
list coming?

96
00:05:15,577 --> 00:05:16,993
Hmm?

97
00:05:19,659 --> 00:05:22,783
I’m sorry,
muffin.

98
00:05:22,784 --> 00:05:25,117
Did the meeting
go badly?

99
00:05:27,367 --> 00:05:30,324
It went
splendidly.

100
00:05:30,325 --> 00:05:32,951
They’re very enthusiastic
about poetry.

101
00:05:34,033 --> 00:05:37,032
Particularly Keats.

102
00:05:37,033 --> 00:05:38,866
Terrific.

103
00:05:38,867 --> 00:05:41,365
How’s about a nice,
big Caesar salad?

104
00:05:41,366 --> 00:05:42,991
Lots of anchovies.

105
00:05:42,992 --> 00:05:44,866
I’m starving.

106
00:05:47,742 --> 00:05:50,157
You feel like
a Caesar salad?

107
00:05:50,158 --> 00:05:51,783
TOM:
Yeah.

108
00:05:53,241 --> 00:05:55,616
Is that what
you want?

109
00:05:59,450 --> 00:06:00,573
[CLATTERS]

110
00:06:00,574 --> 00:06:03,282
Go on playing house?

111
00:06:03,283 --> 00:06:05,032
What?

112
00:06:06,825 --> 00:06:10,323
Bridgette. Bridgette.

113
00:06:10,324 --> 00:06:13,365
Isn’t that her name?
Your new paralegal.

114
00:06:13,366 --> 00:06:15,572
I recognized those
ridiculously long legs.

115
00:06:15,573 --> 00:06:16,948
What are you
talking about?

116
00:06:16,949 --> 00:06:19,533
I saw you,
Tom.

117
00:06:23,907 --> 00:06:28,031
I planted those gardenias
that you gave to her.

118
00:06:29,366 --> 00:06:30,656
I’m sorry,
Mags.

119
00:06:30,657 --> 00:06:33,239
That’s it?

120
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:35,406
That’s all you
have to say?

121
00:06:35,407 --> 00:06:37,071
It just happened.

122
00:06:37,072 --> 00:06:39,656
Here? In our house?

123
00:06:39,657 --> 00:06:41,572
Which room did it
happen in, Tom?

124
00:06:41,573 --> 00:06:43,323
Let’s cool it,
okay?

125
00:06:43,324 --> 00:06:47,323
For 25 years, I have
come home to you.

126
00:06:47,324 --> 00:06:49,656
Was it so difficult?

127
00:06:51,322 --> 00:06:53,739
I’m the one who dropped out
of college to work

128
00:06:53,740 --> 00:06:56,281
so you could go
to law school.

129
00:06:56,282 --> 00:06:58,029
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

130
00:06:58,030 --> 00:07:01,489
Oh, don’t answer that phone.
Turn off the phone.

131
00:07:05,865 --> 00:07:08,488
What do you
want me to say?

132
00:07:08,489 --> 00:07:12,113
Is there anything I can
say that’ll make it okay?

133
00:07:12,114 --> 00:07:15,237
I don’t know. I want you to
say that I didn’t see right.

134
00:07:15,238 --> 00:07:16,948
What happened?

135
00:07:18,448 --> 00:07:19,905
I fell in love.

136
00:07:19,906 --> 00:07:21,821
Oh, my God.

137
00:07:36,197 --> 00:07:37,780
MAGGIE:
Happiness forever.

138
00:07:40,655 --> 00:07:44,028
With a man
who’s your soul mate.

139
00:07:44,029 --> 00:07:46,446
Fresh dew
on your eyelids.

140
00:07:48,822 --> 00:07:51,487
And your
own bathroom.

141
00:07:53,654 --> 00:07:55,153
After years of controversy,

142
00:07:55,154 --> 00:07:57,779
during which John Keats’
work had been,

143
00:07:57,780 --> 00:08:00,654
alternately,
savagely criticized,

144
00:08:00,655 --> 00:08:02,778
and extravagantly praised,

145
00:08:02,779 --> 00:08:05,820
and then finally,
neglected.

146
00:08:05,821 --> 00:08:08,527
[BELL RINGS]

147
00:08:08,528 --> 00:08:12,486
His position as one of England’s
finest poets has been confirmed.

148
00:08:12,487 --> 00:08:14,610
Have a great summer
everybody.

149
00:08:14,611 --> 00:08:16,612
[STUDENTS CLAPPING]

150
00:08:18,362 --> 00:08:20,863
[STUDENTS CHATTERING]

151
00:08:22,487 --> 00:08:24,528
Oh, Mrs. Weber.
Yes.

152
00:08:24,529 --> 00:08:26,194
Listening to you talk
about Keats

153
00:08:26,195 --> 00:08:28,693
with such passion
this semester,

154
00:08:28,694 --> 00:08:31,777
well,
would you read this?

155
00:08:31,778 --> 00:08:33,986
Oh, sure, Jennifer.

156
00:08:45,904 --> 00:08:48,528
It’s beautiful,
Jennifer.

157
00:08:48,529 --> 00:08:50,526
You have
real talent.

158
00:08:50,527 --> 00:08:51,736
Did you
know that?

159
00:08:51,737 --> 00:08:53,485
Really?

160
00:08:53,486 --> 00:08:54,986
Well, thank you.

161
00:08:54,987 --> 00:08:57,401
You gave me the
courage to write it.

162
00:08:57,402 --> 00:08:58,943
Have a great summer,
Mrs. W.

163
00:08:58,944 --> 00:09:00,362
Thanks.

164
00:09:18,568 --> 00:09:20,318
[♪♪♪]

165
00:09:20,319 --> 00:09:22,360
Oh, hey,
Jim Rogers.

166
00:09:22,361 --> 00:09:25,025
Just trying to be a gentleman.

167
00:09:25,026 --> 00:09:26,900
What a relief.

168
00:09:26,901 --> 00:09:29,068
Chivalry’s not dead.

169
00:09:29,069 --> 00:09:32,025
And I’m looking forward
to these, uh, weeks off.

170
00:09:32,026 --> 00:09:33,942
You?

171
00:09:33,943 --> 00:09:36,358
Um, yeah, sort of.

172
00:09:36,359 --> 00:09:38,401
It’s been an unusual
three months.

173
00:09:38,402 --> 00:09:40,693
I know.
Thanks.

174
00:09:45,110 --> 00:09:49,066
Uh, do you like
The Stones?

175
00:09:51,442 --> 00:09:54,400
Keith Richards, Charlie Watts,
the guy with the lips.

176
00:09:54,401 --> 00:09:56,399
Um, yes.

177
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:58,443
I thought you
would.

178
00:10:00,567 --> 00:10:02,358
Third row.

179
00:10:02,359 --> 00:10:04,065
They’re gonna be here
on the 26th.

180
00:10:04,066 --> 00:10:07,857
Been to every Stones concert
around here since 1972.

181
00:10:07,858 --> 00:10:09,316
Oh, fantastic.

182
00:10:09,317 --> 00:10:13,818
And would you, uh,
like to go with me?

183
00:10:17,984 --> 00:10:19,483
Um...

184
00:10:20,816 --> 00:10:22,858
Thank you,
but...

185
00:10:27,441 --> 00:10:29,024
Okay.

186
00:10:32,775 --> 00:10:35,856
Everybody knows how
devoted Jim Rogers was

187
00:10:35,857 --> 00:10:37,522
throughout
his wife’s cancer.

188
00:10:37,523 --> 00:10:40,439
I mean, come on,
he’s a damn jewel.

189
00:10:40,440 --> 00:10:41,939
Would you just
lay off me?

190
00:10:41,940 --> 00:10:44,148
Everyone has
a solution.

191
00:10:44,149 --> 00:10:46,148
Then help yourself.

192
00:10:48,150 --> 00:10:51,440
I was married
for 25 years.

193
00:10:51,441 --> 00:10:54,814
I slept next to someone
I thought I knew,

194
00:10:54,815 --> 00:10:56,939
every night
for 25 years.

195
00:10:56,940 --> 00:10:59,689
And, suddenly,
it’s over!

196
00:10:59,690 --> 00:11:00,980
What am I
supposed to do?

197
00:11:00,981 --> 00:11:04,438
Just shake myself
and just snap to?

198
00:11:04,439 --> 00:11:06,690
Yes, exactly.
Oh, God.

199
00:11:06,691 --> 00:11:08,855
Come on.
Tom isn’t worth it, Maggie.

200
00:11:08,856 --> 00:11:12,563
Oh, just...
Would you just knock it off?

201
00:11:12,564 --> 00:11:15,523
Fran’s husband knows
a lawyer in Tom’s firm.

202
00:11:15,524 --> 00:11:17,938
And he says that
Tom was well-known

203
00:11:17,939 --> 00:11:21,313
for dipping into
the paralegal pool.

204
00:11:21,314 --> 00:11:24,231
Maggie, this was not
the first time.

205
00:11:27,647 --> 00:11:29,649
[CLOCK TICKING]

206
00:11:41,146 --> 00:11:42,730
[♪♪♪]

207
00:13:04,895 --> 00:13:07,060
NANCY:
You’re going to take
a sabbatical?

208
00:13:07,061 --> 00:13:09,144
Why didn’t
you tell us?

209
00:13:09,145 --> 00:13:11,476
I just decided
yesterday.

210
00:13:11,477 --> 00:13:13,143
Maggie, you
are so secretive.

211
00:13:13,144 --> 00:13:15,892
No, Maggie’s
just private.

212
00:13:15,893 --> 00:13:18,643
So where are you going?
Up north.

213
00:13:18,644 --> 00:13:22,018
To an unbelievably beautiful
spot called Little Bear Lake.

214
00:13:22,019 --> 00:13:23,977
Little Bear Lake?

215
00:13:23,978 --> 00:13:26,977
Yeah, there’s a restaurant,
a dance hall there

216
00:13:26,978 --> 00:13:29,768
where I spent one of the
happiest summers of my life.

217
00:13:29,769 --> 00:13:32,309
I was eighteen,
waiting tables.

218
00:13:32,310 --> 00:13:34,894
I want to go back there
and find that girl.

219
00:13:34,895 --> 00:13:36,184
You haven’t been in touch

220
00:13:36,185 --> 00:13:38,102
with anybody up there
all this time?

221
00:13:38,103 --> 00:13:39,559
No.

222
00:13:39,560 --> 00:13:41,810
There’s one person,
though, in particular,

223
00:13:41,811 --> 00:13:43,184
I’ve always
wondered about.

224
00:13:43,185 --> 00:13:45,393
A male person?

225
00:13:45,394 --> 00:13:49,516
Patrick Fleming.

226
00:13:49,517 --> 00:13:54,393
He was... Oh, God,
he was my first love.

227
00:13:54,394 --> 00:13:57,059
Handsome and gentle.
Hmm?

228
00:13:57,060 --> 00:13:59,850
No. I was too young.

229
00:13:59,851 --> 00:14:01,766
But it didn’t stop me
from wanting him.

230
00:14:01,767 --> 00:14:04,891
Didn’t take a breath that summer
without thinking of Patrick.

231
00:14:04,892 --> 00:14:06,142
That is romantic.

232
00:14:06,143 --> 00:14:08,435
I found his letters.

233
00:14:10,851 --> 00:14:13,100
I haven’t a clue
what happened to him.

234
00:14:16,059 --> 00:14:19,558
You’re not going up there
because of this Patrick guy,

235
00:14:19,559 --> 00:14:22,349
hoping you
and he might...?

236
00:14:22,350 --> 00:14:25,766
No, I’m going
up there

237
00:14:25,767 --> 00:14:28,641
because I want
to sort out my life.

238
00:14:28,642 --> 00:14:32,057
And I wanna see
the old dance hall again.

239
00:14:32,058 --> 00:14:35,433
Patrick and I
had this secret place.

240
00:14:36,808 --> 00:14:38,682
It was a dock
that he had built.

241
00:14:38,683 --> 00:14:42,057
And we used to go there and
recite poetry to one another.

242
00:14:42,058 --> 00:14:43,806
Does that sound
hopelessly sappy?

243
00:14:43,807 --> 00:14:45,640
No.

244
00:14:45,641 --> 00:14:48,351
No, it wasn’t.
It was... It was perfect.

245
00:14:50,141 --> 00:14:53,558
What happened?
I ended it.

246
00:14:54,975 --> 00:14:58,098
I’m worried about
your expectations, Mom.

247
00:14:58,099 --> 00:15:01,639
This guy’s probably
married with 10 kids.

248
00:15:01,640 --> 00:15:02,808
I’m not
expecting him

249
00:15:02,809 --> 00:15:05,514
to be waiting for me
on our dock.

250
00:15:05,515 --> 00:15:08,097
I just don’t want you
to be hurt anymore, okay?

251
00:15:08,098 --> 00:15:10,599
It’s enough Dad’s living
with Bridgette so soon,

252
00:15:10,600 --> 00:15:11,973
that bastard.

253
00:15:11,974 --> 00:15:14,097
Don’t you ever call
your father a bastard.

254
00:15:14,098 --> 00:15:16,098
I’m okay.

255
00:15:16,099 --> 00:15:18,057
I’m better than okay.
I’m excited.

256
00:15:19,932 --> 00:15:22,765
You gonna be
okay?

257
00:15:22,766 --> 00:15:24,014
I love you.

258
00:15:24,015 --> 00:15:26,015
[♪♪♪]

259
00:17:54,718 --> 00:17:55,968
[DOOR OPENS]

260
00:17:57,803 --> 00:17:59,634
MAN:
What are you doing here, lady?

261
00:17:59,635 --> 00:18:00,842
[DOOR CLOSES]

262
00:18:00,843 --> 00:18:02,719
Oh, I’m just looking
for the owner.

263
00:18:02,720 --> 00:18:05,218
I can’t hear what you’re saying.
My batteries are low.

264
00:18:05,219 --> 00:18:07,009
You’re breaking the law,
you know, you’re trespassing.

265
00:18:07,010 --> 00:18:10,967
I saw you from my place.
I’m just looking around.

266
00:18:10,968 --> 00:18:13,633
Um, how long has
this place been closed?

267
00:18:13,634 --> 00:18:14,801
A few years.

268
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,760
Come on,
you’ve gotta go.

269
00:18:18,093 --> 00:18:19,593
Mr. Finnegan.

270
00:18:19,594 --> 00:18:21,384
Gil?
What?

271
00:18:21,385 --> 00:18:23,424
It’s so nice
to see you again.

272
00:18:23,425 --> 00:18:27,217
Maggie Patterson.
I used to work here.

273
00:18:27,218 --> 00:18:29,009
How is Harriet?

274
00:18:29,010 --> 00:18:31,008
Same as she’s
always been.

275
00:18:31,009 --> 00:18:33,177
Who are you?

276
00:18:36,593 --> 00:18:38,466
Maggie!

277
00:18:38,467 --> 00:18:40,425
Oh, yes.

278
00:18:40,426 --> 00:18:43,924
Those blue eyes.
You don’t forget.

279
00:18:43,925 --> 00:18:46,632
You’re the one who
couldn’t balance your tray.

280
00:18:46,633 --> 00:18:49,174
Well, a few beer bottles
did hit the deck.

281
00:18:49,175 --> 00:18:50,800
What a coincidence.

282
00:18:50,801 --> 00:18:53,633
An old friend of yours
just came up here too.

283
00:18:53,634 --> 00:18:57,341
Someone you were
very close with.

284
00:18:57,342 --> 00:19:00,008
Oh, who was that?

285
00:19:00,009 --> 00:19:03,048
Our daughter,
Claire.

286
00:19:03,049 --> 00:19:04,717
Oh.

287
00:19:06,009 --> 00:19:07,465
Great.

288
00:19:07,466 --> 00:19:09,800
[♪♪♪]

289
00:19:09,801 --> 00:19:11,923
I thoroughly enjoyed
each marriage.

290
00:19:11,924 --> 00:19:14,298
Until the crash landing.

291
00:19:14,299 --> 00:19:15,925
Oh, they’re tough.

292
00:19:15,926 --> 00:19:17,632
Very.

293
00:19:17,633 --> 00:19:20,799
But you just have to get
back up on the horse.

294
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:22,590
Yeah.
Yeah.

295
00:19:22,591 --> 00:19:25,091
Oh, I, um,
I grabbed this.

296
00:19:25,092 --> 00:19:28,716
Oh, wait.
Out of a box of old memories.

297
00:19:28,717 --> 00:19:31,466
This is gonna
take you back.

298
00:19:34,883 --> 00:19:37,049
How unafraid
we were.

299
00:19:37,050 --> 00:19:39,132
We really believed we could
do anything, didn’t we?

300
00:19:39,133 --> 00:19:42,132
Oh, yes. Remember how
passionate we were?

301
00:19:42,133 --> 00:19:43,464
Oh.

302
00:19:43,465 --> 00:19:45,963
We were gonna
stop the bombing.

303
00:19:45,964 --> 00:19:48,423
End the war, bring
the troops back home.

304
00:19:48,424 --> 00:19:50,714
And we did it.

305
00:19:50,715 --> 00:19:53,256
Oh, how we used to
argue for hours

306
00:19:53,257 --> 00:19:55,297
over every
conceivable topic.

307
00:19:55,298 --> 00:19:59,214
Patrick was...
He was good at that.

308
00:19:59,215 --> 00:20:01,715
He was good
at everything.

309
00:20:01,716 --> 00:20:04,673
Well, to survival.
Right.

310
00:20:04,674 --> 00:20:07,047
And old friends.

311
00:20:07,048 --> 00:20:08,547
Uhm.

312
00:20:08,548 --> 00:20:11,547
Somehow I always knew,

313
00:20:11,548 --> 00:20:13,755
even after you didn’t
come back that summer

314
00:20:13,756 --> 00:20:15,046
and we never
heard from you.

315
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:18,590
Still, I just knew
I’d see you again.

316
00:20:20,590 --> 00:20:22,588
Well, I wrote
to Patrick after.

317
00:20:22,589 --> 00:20:25,921
I told him why I couldn’t
come back to the Harvest Moon.

318
00:20:25,922 --> 00:20:27,380
Didn’t he ever talk
about me?

319
00:20:27,381 --> 00:20:29,298
Uh-hmm.
He wouldn’t.

320
00:20:30,505 --> 00:20:33,337
My father was sick.

321
00:20:33,338 --> 00:20:35,713
My mother had
just died.

322
00:20:35,714 --> 00:20:37,420
He was in such
a panic

323
00:20:37,421 --> 00:20:39,213
that if I came back
here to Patrick,

324
00:20:39,214 --> 00:20:40,839
I would never go
home again.

325
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:44,963
I devoted all my time
to my dad.

326
00:20:44,964 --> 00:20:47,879
It just...
It just took me over.

327
00:20:47,880 --> 00:20:51,088
When I wrote to Patrick,
I asked him

328
00:20:51,089 --> 00:20:54,129
if it wouldn’t be better
if we broke up.

329
00:20:54,130 --> 00:20:56,963
And he never responded.
He never wrote back.

330
00:20:56,964 --> 00:21:00,295
It’s important to me that
I straighten things out.

331
00:21:00,296 --> 00:21:02,255
I want to tell him
I’m sorry for what I...

332
00:21:02,256 --> 00:21:04,128
For what I did
and for what I didn’t do.

333
00:21:04,129 --> 00:21:06,003
But Maggie...

334
00:21:06,004 --> 00:21:08,463
He’s married with 10 kids.
I know, I know.

335
00:21:08,464 --> 00:21:10,420
Well, after that summer,
he did marry a girl

336
00:21:12,462 --> 00:21:14,253
that he met over
in Twin Falls.

337
00:21:14,254 --> 00:21:17,421
She was pregnant.

338
00:21:17,422 --> 00:21:18,920
Is he still with her?

339
00:21:20,755 --> 00:21:22,877
Patrick’s dead.

340
00:21:22,878 --> 00:21:24,294
Heart attack.

341
00:21:24,295 --> 00:21:26,128
Quite a few years ago.

342
00:21:26,129 --> 00:21:28,128
[♪♪♪]

343
00:21:34,128 --> 00:21:36,170
I’m so sorry.

344
00:21:42,961 --> 00:21:44,962
[♪♪♪]

345
00:22:08,753 --> 00:22:10,210
HARRIET:
Reopen The Moon?

346
00:22:10,211 --> 00:22:12,502
It’s more decrepit
than we are.

347
00:22:12,503 --> 00:22:13,876
Speak
for yourself.

348
00:22:13,877 --> 00:22:15,669
Oh,
put that out.

349
00:22:15,670 --> 00:22:18,502
I wanna open The Moon
and fix it up.

350
00:22:18,503 --> 00:22:21,085
So it gleams
the way it used to.

351
00:22:21,086 --> 00:22:24,918
And rocks with music
and life and fun.

352
00:22:24,919 --> 00:22:26,918
And I wanna open
in eight weeks,

353
00:22:26,919 --> 00:22:29,585
on the night of the
actual Harvest Moon.

354
00:22:29,586 --> 00:22:31,793
It’s the most romantic
night of the year.

355
00:22:31,794 --> 00:22:34,417
It won’t work.
The Moon’s up for sale.

356
00:22:34,418 --> 00:22:35,918
If we
open it again,

357
00:22:35,919 --> 00:22:37,794
we’ll be right down there
working with you.

358
00:22:39,877 --> 00:22:42,083
I’ll buy it then.

359
00:22:42,084 --> 00:22:43,875
I approve, I approve.

360
00:22:43,876 --> 00:22:47,292
Just borrowing money
for a dance hall?

361
00:22:47,293 --> 00:22:51,125
I’ve never let myself go.
I’ve always wanted to and I...

362
00:22:51,126 --> 00:22:54,625
I’ve never
listened to myself.

363
00:22:54,626 --> 00:22:56,834
This is my chance
to move forward.

364
00:22:56,835 --> 00:22:58,251
DIANE:
I hear you, Mom.

365
00:22:59,418 --> 00:23:02,624
I’m sorry about that man,
Patrick.

366
00:23:02,625 --> 00:23:04,917
Must have been
a bummer.

367
00:23:04,918 --> 00:23:08,124
I’m gonna try
and put him to rest.

368
00:23:08,125 --> 00:23:09,333
Financial statements.

369
00:23:09,334 --> 00:23:12,124
Uh, list all your assets,

370
00:23:12,125 --> 00:23:17,543
bank accounts, real estate,
stocks, cars, boats.

371
00:23:19,418 --> 00:23:21,415
And, uh, since you’re
on sabbatical

372
00:23:21,416 --> 00:23:23,708
with only half your income,
Mrs. Weber,

373
00:23:23,709 --> 00:23:27,458
we do require
a, uh, co-signer

374
00:23:27,459 --> 00:23:32,957
who, in effect, will guarantee
the loan in case of default.

375
00:23:32,958 --> 00:23:35,416
Have any idea who you might
get to co-sign for you?

376
00:23:35,417 --> 00:23:37,374
I have several
possibilities.

377
00:23:38,624 --> 00:23:40,957
Mr. Stanton.
Paul.

378
00:23:40,958 --> 00:23:43,540
MAGGIE:
Oh, right.
If I fill this in now,

379
00:23:43,541 --> 00:23:44,999
when am I gonna
get the loan?

380
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,666
Um, if everything’s in order,
six to eight weeks.

381
00:23:47,667 --> 00:23:50,874
No! I have to
open in eight weeks.

382
00:23:50,875 --> 00:23:53,208
I have to get the word out
that The Moon is open

383
00:23:53,209 --> 00:23:54,957
for the rest of
the year.

384
00:23:54,958 --> 00:23:57,457
And we want to open on the night
of the actual Harvest Moon.

385
00:23:57,458 --> 00:23:58,998
It’s eight weeks.

386
00:23:58,999 --> 00:24:00,665
Well...
[CHUCKLES]

387
00:24:00,666 --> 00:24:04,622
Well, we have to be sensitive
to your calendar, don’t we?

388
00:24:04,623 --> 00:24:07,330
I mean,
being the friendly bank.

389
00:24:07,331 --> 00:24:08,623
I’ll tell you what.

390
00:24:08,624 --> 00:24:10,956
If you can get a
co-signer right away,

391
00:24:10,957 --> 00:24:12,665
I will guarantee
the loan.

392
00:24:12,666 --> 00:24:14,707
And you can get started
on these repairs.

393
00:24:14,708 --> 00:24:17,332
Well, I have
some savings back home.

394
00:24:17,333 --> 00:24:19,706
And Harriet says
that I can stay upstairs

395
00:24:19,707 --> 00:24:22,205
at the Moon for
a while, so...

396
00:24:22,206 --> 00:24:24,498
[SIGHS]
Ah.

397
00:24:24,499 --> 00:24:26,541
[♪♪♪]

398
00:25:16,997 --> 00:25:18,248
Hi.

399
00:25:20,704 --> 00:25:22,580
Hi.

400
00:25:23,497 --> 00:25:25,953
Are you... You lost?

401
00:25:25,954 --> 00:25:28,079
MAGGIE:
No.

402
00:25:28,080 --> 00:25:29,787
Um,
I know this area.

403
00:25:29,788 --> 00:25:32,163
I’m just
wandering about.

404
00:25:41,079 --> 00:25:43,870
MAGGIE:
Excuse me. Is this your dock?

405
00:25:43,871 --> 00:25:45,786
No. But, uh...

406
00:25:45,787 --> 00:25:47,577
Actually,
my father built it.

407
00:25:47,578 --> 00:25:50,078
A long time ago.

408
00:25:50,079 --> 00:25:52,079
Who was your father?

409
00:25:52,080 --> 00:25:54,495
MAN:
Patrick Fleming.

410
00:25:54,496 --> 00:25:57,454
I’m John Fleming.

411
00:25:58,162 --> 00:25:59,954
Hi, I’m Maggie.

412
00:26:00,787 --> 00:26:02,829
Hi, Maggie.

413
00:26:08,496 --> 00:26:11,329
Are you sure I can’t
help you with anything?

414
00:26:12,619 --> 00:26:15,035
No.

415
00:26:15,036 --> 00:26:17,454
I’m staying
up the hill.

416
00:26:24,161 --> 00:26:26,162
[♪♪♪]

417
00:26:50,328 --> 00:26:52,494
Diane told me about
this dance hall thing.

418
00:26:52,495 --> 00:26:54,368
Is this your way
of getting back at me?

419
00:26:54,369 --> 00:26:56,618
You really do think everything
is about you, don’t you?

420
00:26:56,619 --> 00:26:58,535
I’m sorry, but you must
be getting in touch

421
00:26:58,536 --> 00:27:00,950
with some long hidden part
of your inner psyche,

422
00:27:00,951 --> 00:27:04,075
but it’s way beyond anything
reasonable or responsible.

423
00:27:04,076 --> 00:27:06,534
That is a little odd
coming from you.

424
00:27:06,535 --> 00:27:09,617
What do you know about
running a dance hall?

425
00:27:09,618 --> 00:27:12,867
Look, I’m not asking you
for your stamp of approval.

426
00:27:12,868 --> 00:27:14,909
I just need you to
co-sign the loan.

427
00:27:14,910 --> 00:27:17,075
There’s some money
in the house, my share.

428
00:27:17,076 --> 00:27:20,118
Yeah, but you won’t put
the house on the market.

429
00:27:20,119 --> 00:27:23,075
It’s not worth anything
if we don’t sell it.

430
00:27:23,076 --> 00:27:24,783
I’m not ready to
sell my house.

431
00:27:24,784 --> 00:27:27,659
Our house.
Our house.

432
00:27:27,660 --> 00:27:29,617
This means
a lot to me.

433
00:27:29,618 --> 00:27:32,033
I would appreciate
your help.

434
00:27:32,034 --> 00:27:34,366
Look, uh, I’ve got
an early meeting...

435
00:27:34,367 --> 00:27:36,158
No, no, no,
Tom!

436
00:27:36,159 --> 00:27:37,826
It can’t wait.

437
00:27:41,743 --> 00:27:43,116
Put the house
on the market.

438
00:27:43,117 --> 00:27:46,365
Well now you’re
making some sense.

439
00:27:46,366 --> 00:27:49,158
Look, you send me the facts
on this dance hall thing

440
00:27:49,159 --> 00:27:51,449
and I’ll consider
co-signing the loan

441
00:27:51,450 --> 00:27:52,740
after we sell
the house.

442
00:27:52,741 --> 00:27:54,408
Go to hell!

443
00:27:54,409 --> 00:27:55,741
Just you go to hell!

444
00:27:59,283 --> 00:28:02,116
Listen, everybody,
this is the great woman

445
00:28:02,117 --> 00:28:04,824
who’s opening
the Harvest Moon again.

446
00:28:04,825 --> 00:28:06,658
No, no!
We hope! We hope!

447
00:28:06,659 --> 00:28:09,116
We hope! We hope!

448
00:28:10,658 --> 00:28:12,574
Hi.

449
00:28:15,116 --> 00:28:18,324
Does that mean
we’ve got the loan?

450
00:28:18,325 --> 00:28:19,573
I can’t take
rejection.

451
00:28:19,574 --> 00:28:20,782
Never could.
Right.

452
00:28:20,783 --> 00:28:22,116
I think it was
just a wave.

453
00:28:22,117 --> 00:28:23,448
I called him.

454
00:28:23,449 --> 00:28:25,239
Told him I didn’t have
a co-signer.

455
00:28:25,240 --> 00:28:28,073
He wasn’t thrilled.
Oh, bummer.

456
00:28:28,074 --> 00:28:29,533
Well...

457
00:28:30,825 --> 00:28:32,448
I got them.

458
00:28:39,533 --> 00:28:41,030
Is that
John’s wife?

459
00:28:41,031 --> 00:28:43,490
On the verge,
I hear.

460
00:28:43,491 --> 00:28:45,782
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

461
00:28:45,783 --> 00:28:47,698
Let’s hear it for
the goalie, huh?

462
00:28:47,699 --> 00:28:50,823
Nine saves!
[LAUGHS]

463
00:28:52,449 --> 00:28:55,449
[INDISTINCT CHATTERING]

464
00:28:57,072 --> 00:28:58,615
MAN:
What you got
cooking there?

465
00:29:00,366 --> 00:29:02,365
[LEAVES RUSTLING]

466
00:29:03,698 --> 00:29:05,321
Mrs. Weber?

467
00:29:05,322 --> 00:29:08,572
Oh, call me Maggie.
Great, Maggie.

468
00:29:08,573 --> 00:29:11,280
Um, so you don’t go through
the weekend in suspense.

469
00:29:11,281 --> 00:29:13,947
Oh, God.
What?

470
00:29:13,948 --> 00:29:16,573
We’re gonna give you the
loan on the Harvest Moon.

471
00:29:17,655 --> 00:29:20,113
Without a co-signer?
Yes.

472
00:29:20,114 --> 00:29:23,988
It’s irregular but, uh,
we want the Moon to reopen.

473
00:29:23,989 --> 00:29:26,822
It’s a big deal
around here.

474
00:29:26,823 --> 00:29:30,823
It used to be called the
Treasure of Little Bear Lake.

475
00:29:32,364 --> 00:29:34,196
Thank you! Thank you!

476
00:29:34,197 --> 00:29:36,570
I’m gonna try and make it
an even greater treasure.

477
00:29:36,571 --> 00:29:38,279
Sure you will.
Listen,

478
00:29:38,280 --> 00:29:41,030
we’re delighted
to have you here.

479
00:29:41,031 --> 00:29:43,487
Uh, yeah.
Thank you.

480
00:29:43,488 --> 00:29:44,945
Appreciate it.
You’re welcome.

481
00:29:44,946 --> 00:29:47,655
[♪♪♪]

482
00:29:50,031 --> 00:29:52,154
JOHN:
Maggie? Hi.

483
00:29:52,155 --> 00:29:55,571
You’re Maggie Patterson, right?
John Fleming.

484
00:29:55,572 --> 00:29:57,361
I hear you’re gonna
reopen The Moon.

485
00:29:57,362 --> 00:29:58,778
Yes.

486
00:29:58,779 --> 00:30:01,528
Well, I’m sort of
a jack of all trades.

487
00:30:01,529 --> 00:30:02,945
You can ask anyone.

488
00:30:02,946 --> 00:30:04,987
And, uh,
I carve wood too.

489
00:30:04,988 --> 00:30:09,445
Although it’s kind of hard
to make a living out of that.

490
00:30:09,446 --> 00:30:12,194
If you’re hiring,
I’ll work very hard for you.

491
00:30:12,195 --> 00:30:14,736
I figure whatever you need,
I can get it for you.

492
00:30:14,737 --> 00:30:16,737
I know everybody
in town.

493
00:30:16,738 --> 00:30:19,446
I’m not gonna let anyone put
their hand in your pocket.

494
00:30:19,447 --> 00:30:21,361
I know your father
was the architect

495
00:30:21,362 --> 00:30:23,569
who restored
the Moon in the ’70s.

496
00:30:23,570 --> 00:30:24,903
God, I always wondered

497
00:30:24,904 --> 00:30:26,820
what he was like
when he was younger.

498
00:30:26,821 --> 00:30:29,569
I know he was completely
into his work.

499
00:30:29,570 --> 00:30:31,862
’Cause I get that
from him.

500
00:30:31,863 --> 00:30:35,153
Although he could be
a little grandiose at times.

501
00:30:35,154 --> 00:30:37,403
Grandiose?
Oh, yeah.

502
00:30:37,404 --> 00:30:39,693
John Keats Fleming.

503
00:30:39,694 --> 00:30:41,569
He named me after
the poet.

504
00:30:41,570 --> 00:30:43,736
I’d say that’s
pretty grandiose.

505
00:30:43,737 --> 00:30:45,818
Gives you something
to live up to.

506
00:30:45,819 --> 00:30:48,736
Named after a poet.
Yeah.

507
00:30:48,737 --> 00:30:51,985
I try not to be
too intimidated though.

508
00:30:51,986 --> 00:30:56,111
So you gonna take
a chance on me?

509
00:30:58,570 --> 00:31:00,819
Sign me on
as your foreman.

510
00:31:01,818 --> 00:31:03,651
I’ll give it
a try.

511
00:31:03,652 --> 00:31:04,735
See you
Monday morning.

512
00:31:04,736 --> 00:31:05,987
Early.

513
00:31:07,777 --> 00:31:09,153
Thank you.

514
00:31:18,569 --> 00:31:20,610
[♪♪♪]

515
00:31:20,611 --> 00:31:22,610
[WORKERS HAMMERING]

516
00:31:28,651 --> 00:31:29,859
MAN:
It’s almost over.

517
00:31:29,860 --> 00:31:31,860
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

518
00:31:45,569 --> 00:31:47,901
Oh, my God!

519
00:31:53,859 --> 00:31:55,817
HARRIET:
Maggie!

520
00:31:55,818 --> 00:31:58,859
We have to admit, we’re excited
about what’s going on here!

521
00:31:58,860 --> 00:32:00,775
We’d like to
offer our services.

522
00:32:00,776 --> 00:32:02,732
And it won’t cost
you a cent.

523
00:32:02,733 --> 00:32:06,150
Advice, chores,
hand-holding.

524
00:32:06,151 --> 00:32:07,692
Oh, we just
can’t stay away.

525
00:32:07,693 --> 00:32:09,692
Well, this is an offer
I can’t resist.

526
00:32:09,693 --> 00:32:10,941
CLAIRE: Maggie!
Thank you.

527
00:32:10,942 --> 00:32:12,234
Maggie!
Yeah.

528
00:32:12,235 --> 00:32:13,858
Can I speak with you
for a minute, please?

529
00:32:13,859 --> 00:32:15,276
Madam?

530
00:32:16,068 --> 00:32:17,690
These, um...

531
00:32:17,691 --> 00:32:20,857
These records that you asked
me to order for the jukebox?

532
00:32:20,858 --> 00:32:25,983
Some Enchanted Evening?
Light My Fire? You Send Me?

533
00:32:25,984 --> 00:32:27,400
What about
them?

534
00:32:27,401 --> 00:32:31,649
These were Patrick’s
favorites, weren’t they?

535
00:32:31,650 --> 00:32:33,649
Well, why tear
yourself up?

536
00:32:33,650 --> 00:32:35,941
Going back to Patrick
and the past...

537
00:32:35,942 --> 00:32:37,816
Well...

538
00:32:37,817 --> 00:32:40,191
Look at that list.
There’s current ones.

539
00:32:40,192 --> 00:32:43,440
Maggie, come on.

540
00:32:43,441 --> 00:32:45,733
Well, part of the reason
for me coming up here,

541
00:32:45,734 --> 00:32:49,898
this whole journey was just
to reconnect with a happy time.

542
00:32:49,899 --> 00:32:53,981
Come out refreshed
and with my head together.

543
00:32:53,982 --> 00:32:56,898
Hey, good. I just
hope that all this work

544
00:32:56,899 --> 00:32:58,898
is building something
for your future,

545
00:32:58,899 --> 00:33:01,065
not getting you stuck
in the past.

546
00:33:01,066 --> 00:33:04,649
Ladies, I found a great buy on
lilies for the front entrance.

547
00:33:04,650 --> 00:33:06,856
My dad had this picture
of the place years ago

548
00:33:06,857 --> 00:33:09,398
with all these lilies out
in front and it was great.

549
00:33:09,399 --> 00:33:11,689
I almost forgot.
You have to decide

550
00:33:11,690 --> 00:33:13,731
whether you want to
paint the dance floor

551
00:33:13,732 --> 00:33:16,149
or if you want stain
and seal coats.

552
00:33:17,356 --> 00:33:20,940
Oh, well, just check it
with Claire.

553
00:33:26,023 --> 00:33:29,480
Eighty dollars for this ad.
It’s ridiculous.

554
00:33:29,481 --> 00:33:31,063
Let me see.

555
00:33:31,064 --> 00:33:33,896
We should be putting posters up
on telephone poles.

556
00:33:33,897 --> 00:33:36,189
Well, people don’t read
telephone poles.

557
00:33:36,190 --> 00:33:38,855
Maybe John can
get it cheaper.

558
00:33:38,856 --> 00:33:40,939
Well, you
ask him then.

559
00:33:40,940 --> 00:33:43,648
Speaking of
your foreman,

560
00:33:43,649 --> 00:33:45,647
Maggie, he thinks
you’re avoiding him.

561
00:33:45,648 --> 00:33:48,189
And he keeps
asking me why.

562
00:33:48,190 --> 00:33:50,106
He’s uncomfortable.

563
00:33:50,107 --> 00:33:52,438
Well, I don’t know
what to do. I...

564
00:33:52,439 --> 00:33:54,064
I see him and
I think of Patrick,

565
00:33:54,065 --> 00:33:57,355
whom I loved
so much.

566
00:33:57,356 --> 00:33:59,354
My first romance.

567
00:33:59,355 --> 00:34:00,937
There John
is smiling at me,

568
00:34:00,938 --> 00:34:04,104
telling me a section of the roof
has got dry rot and I...

569
00:34:04,105 --> 00:34:05,897
I’m just
shivering inside.

570
00:34:05,898 --> 00:34:07,854
It shakes me up.

571
00:34:07,855 --> 00:34:09,937
Even his hands
are like Patrick’s.

572
00:34:09,938 --> 00:34:13,646
Same broad palms
and long fingers.

573
00:34:13,647 --> 00:34:15,270
You could
get lost in them.

574
00:34:15,271 --> 00:34:16,646
Am I supposed
to tell him that?

575
00:34:16,647 --> 00:34:19,062
Sounds positively
pornographic.

576
00:34:19,063 --> 00:34:20,978
Tell me.

577
00:34:20,979 --> 00:34:24,103
Oh, Maggie,
he is not Patrick.

578
00:34:24,104 --> 00:34:25,646
He’s nothing
like him.

579
00:34:25,647 --> 00:34:28,146
And it’s not nice,
the way you’re treating him.

580
00:34:28,147 --> 00:34:30,188
JOHN:
Maggie?

581
00:34:30,189 --> 00:34:32,144
I’d like to
show you something.

582
00:34:32,145 --> 00:34:35,062
Would you mind coming with me,
please?

583
00:34:35,063 --> 00:34:36,604
Yep.

584
00:34:39,855 --> 00:34:43,687
You’ve got people all excited
about the opening of The Moon.

585
00:34:43,688 --> 00:34:47,102
I want it to be the
biggest event of the year.

586
00:34:47,103 --> 00:34:50,604
I think this town needs
the Harvest Moon.

587
00:34:50,605 --> 00:34:52,352
My dad used to
always go on

588
00:34:52,353 --> 00:34:55,644
about how you could go down
there any night of the week

589
00:34:55,645 --> 00:34:57,644
and you’d always run
into your friends.

590
00:34:57,645 --> 00:35:00,477
And in those days
everyone danced

591
00:35:00,478 --> 00:35:02,937
and nobody cared whether they
looked cool or not.

592
00:35:02,938 --> 00:35:06,437
They just let
themselves go. You know?

593
00:35:06,438 --> 00:35:09,145
I think you’re bringing
that back here.

594
00:35:09,146 --> 00:35:12,311
You think people today
want the same things?

595
00:35:12,312 --> 00:35:14,810
Yeah.

596
00:35:14,811 --> 00:35:16,353
I do.

597
00:35:23,685 --> 00:35:27,103
What do you think?
Oh, you fixed the sign.

598
00:35:30,936 --> 00:35:33,101
That’s the way it looked
in my dad’s photo.

599
00:35:33,102 --> 00:35:34,935
I remember.
It’s just the way it was

600
00:35:34,936 --> 00:35:37,643
when I drove up in
my pale blue Plymouth.

601
00:35:37,644 --> 00:35:39,853
Years ago,
for the first time.

602
00:35:41,352 --> 00:35:42,977
I was so nervous.

603
00:35:42,978 --> 00:35:46,185
I wanted to become part
of the whole thing here.

604
00:35:46,186 --> 00:35:49,642
Well, well, I did.

605
00:35:49,643 --> 00:35:52,892
After breaking 30 beer bottles,
I wasn’t much of a waitress.

606
00:35:52,893 --> 00:35:55,518
I’m amazed Harriet
didn’t fire me.

607
00:36:06,185 --> 00:36:09,727
Look, look.
There’s a monarch.

608
00:36:12,351 --> 00:36:14,726
He’ll probably
hibernate soon.

609
00:36:14,727 --> 00:36:16,601
No, actually,

610
00:36:16,602 --> 00:36:19,101
I think monarchs
are the only butterfly

611
00:36:19,102 --> 00:36:23,517
that migrates thousands
of miles south in the winter.

612
00:36:23,518 --> 00:36:25,935
All with these
delicate wings.

613
00:36:34,434 --> 00:36:35,933
Ah.

614
00:36:37,975 --> 00:36:41,183
Oh, thousands of miles.

615
00:36:41,184 --> 00:36:45,432
God, how could anything
be so determined

616
00:36:45,433 --> 00:36:47,600
and so fragile?

617
00:36:49,975 --> 00:36:52,642
It’s like you.

618
00:36:52,643 --> 00:36:55,266
Doing all of this.

619
00:37:07,432 --> 00:37:09,431
Maggie, there’s been
an accident!

620
00:37:09,432 --> 00:37:10,682
Oh my God!
What happened?

621
00:37:10,683 --> 00:37:12,432
He fell off the roof.
Bring him in.

622
00:37:12,433 --> 00:37:15,348
I’ll call the doctor.
We were putting the tarp up.

623
00:37:15,349 --> 00:37:18,139
The doctor wants you observed
for at least three hours.

624
00:37:18,140 --> 00:37:21,141
So you don’t fall asleep
or lose consciousness.

625
00:37:22,932 --> 00:37:24,474
I should go
home now.

626
00:37:24,475 --> 00:37:27,223
No, you should be lying quietly.
I feel fine.

627
00:37:27,224 --> 00:37:29,558
You should stay at least
one more hour, John.

628
00:37:34,641 --> 00:37:36,681
JOHN:
Claire tells me
you’re a teacher.

629
00:37:36,682 --> 00:37:38,557
What do you teach?

630
00:37:39,724 --> 00:37:41,765
English literature.

631
00:37:41,766 --> 00:37:44,390
JOHN:
Literature. I like that word.

632
00:37:44,391 --> 00:37:47,515
You know, it’s just got
to be good for you.

633
00:37:49,389 --> 00:37:51,598
I wasn’t very
good in school.

634
00:37:51,599 --> 00:37:55,264
Guess, I was more interested
in working with my hands.

635
00:37:55,265 --> 00:37:58,889
Always liked books, though.
It was school that put me off.

636
00:37:58,890 --> 00:38:02,848
Didn’t your father
encourage you to read?

637
00:38:02,849 --> 00:38:06,513
A Keats fan?
Oh, yeah.

638
00:38:06,514 --> 00:38:11,137
He said that I would come to
it eventually, in my own time.

639
00:38:11,138 --> 00:38:12,846
In my own way.

640
00:38:12,847 --> 00:38:15,389
He was right,
of course.

641
00:38:15,390 --> 00:38:18,263
I find myself reading
more and more.

642
00:38:18,264 --> 00:38:20,138
What are some
of your favorite books?

643
00:38:20,139 --> 00:38:22,596
Maybe  Crime and Punishment.

644
00:38:22,597 --> 00:38:24,054
Or  Steppenwolf.

645
00:38:24,055 --> 00:38:26,304
That’s funny.
So many guys love that book.

646
00:38:26,305 --> 00:38:28,679
Is that sarcasm?
No.

647
00:38:28,680 --> 00:38:31,637
No, they’re both fine books,
really.

648
00:38:31,638 --> 00:38:35,554
Recently I read
Wuthering Heights.

649
00:38:35,555 --> 00:38:37,471
Unbelievably romantic.

650
00:38:37,472 --> 00:38:42,179
The characters long
to be together for years.

651
00:38:42,180 --> 00:38:46,221
But when she finally gets
her man, she dies.

652
00:38:46,222 --> 00:38:48,221
In a sense,
she loves the wrong man.

653
00:38:48,222 --> 00:38:50,886
How can you love
the wrong man?

654
00:38:50,887 --> 00:38:52,678
I mean,
love is such a gift.

655
00:38:52,679 --> 00:38:56,387
I think it’s enough
just to love.

656
00:38:56,388 --> 00:38:58,386
Don’t you?
Oh.

657
00:38:58,387 --> 00:39:01,095
I don’t really have
a philosophy.

658
00:39:01,096 --> 00:39:03,095
Not about love,
anyway.

659
00:39:04,888 --> 00:39:07,262
I have sort of been
having a fantasy.

660
00:39:07,263 --> 00:39:10,304
Sort of an exercise to get me
through a difficult phase.

661
00:39:10,305 --> 00:39:13,303
I call it the
Cult of Aphrodite.

662
00:39:13,304 --> 00:39:15,845
All the women
can have five lovers.

663
00:39:15,846 --> 00:39:18,385
And all the men
must be monogamous.

664
00:39:18,386 --> 00:39:19,845
Or they turn
into eunuchs.

665
00:39:19,846 --> 00:39:21,553
Wow.

666
00:39:21,554 --> 00:39:24,052
That must
be some phase.

667
00:39:24,053 --> 00:39:26,595
Yeah.
It is some phase.

668
00:39:26,596 --> 00:39:29,718
Facing that you’re
a supporting player

669
00:39:29,719 --> 00:39:33,888
in other people’s lives
and not truly important.

670
00:39:38,094 --> 00:39:39,468
I didn’t...

671
00:39:39,469 --> 00:39:41,593
I didn’t thank you
for drying my boots off.

672
00:39:41,594 --> 00:39:43,427
I’m gonna have to go
get them wet now.

673
00:39:43,428 --> 00:39:46,593
Oh, there you are.
Oh, sweetie.

674
00:39:46,594 --> 00:39:48,469
Thanks so much for
taking care of him.

675
00:39:48,470 --> 00:39:50,676
JOHN:
Amy, I told you I was okay.

676
00:39:50,677 --> 00:39:52,428
I could have
driven myself.

677
00:39:52,429 --> 00:39:55,136
Honey, you
fell off a roof.

678
00:39:55,137 --> 00:39:58,179
Come on, let’s go.
Come on.

679
00:39:59,719 --> 00:40:01,594
Thanks for
the first aid.

680
00:40:01,595 --> 00:40:03,801
And don’t worry,
we’ll open The Moon on time.

681
00:40:03,802 --> 00:40:06,678
Promise.
Goodnight.

682
00:40:50,760 --> 00:40:53,384
Okay, thanks.
All right.

683
00:40:59,051 --> 00:41:02,425
Uh, they say the Moon’s
foundation is slipping.

684
00:41:02,426 --> 00:41:05,801
We’re gonna have to reinforce it
with concrete and steel.

685
00:41:07,634 --> 00:41:10,923
Well, then we’ll do it.
We have three weeks.

686
00:41:10,924 --> 00:41:14,091
Um, it’s gonna
cost a lot.

687
00:41:26,591 --> 00:41:29,132
That building has been
standing a hundred years.

688
00:41:29,133 --> 00:41:32,590
We can refinance our place,
can’t we, Gil?

689
00:41:32,591 --> 00:41:34,216
Get some money
for this.

690
00:41:34,217 --> 00:41:36,881
Mom, the little equity
you have in your house,

691
00:41:36,882 --> 00:41:38,673
it’s everything
you’ve got.

692
00:41:38,674 --> 00:41:41,422
Now I have some money coming
from my latest divorce.

693
00:41:41,423 --> 00:41:43,590
Uh, but not for
a couple of months.

694
00:41:43,591 --> 00:41:45,424
I could sell my house
back home, but...

695
00:41:45,425 --> 00:41:47,089
it’s not gonna
help us now.

696
00:41:47,090 --> 00:41:51,381
You could
open later.

697
00:41:51,382 --> 00:41:54,173
I was hoping I was gonna be
able to raise part of the money

698
00:41:54,174 --> 00:41:56,006
and you’d give me
a loan for the rest.

699
00:41:56,007 --> 00:41:58,090
I’ve reached the bottom
of my piggy bank.

700
00:41:58,091 --> 00:42:01,339
When you reach the bottom,
you wonder what’s gonna happen.

701
00:42:01,340 --> 00:42:03,300
You wonder
stuff like...

702
00:42:04,965 --> 00:42:06,340
"am I gonna have
a roof over my head?"

703
00:42:06,341 --> 00:42:08,173
Am I gonna starve?
Am I gonna die?

704
00:42:08,174 --> 00:42:10,465
You don’t have to.
No, I know. I know. I know.

705
00:42:10,466 --> 00:42:12,172
I’m not gonna die.

706
00:42:12,173 --> 00:42:15,173
When you reach the bottom,
you... You just feel dead.

707
00:42:15,174 --> 00:42:17,546
Because your dreams
are dying.

708
00:42:17,547 --> 00:42:19,256
And I’m not gonna
let that happen.

709
00:42:19,257 --> 00:42:20,921
I am not gonna
pull out.

710
00:42:20,922 --> 00:42:22,923
I’m gonna open
The Moon,

711
00:42:22,924 --> 00:42:25,964
even if people have to
come and dance on the grass

712
00:42:25,965 --> 00:42:29,171
at the water’s edge, I am gonna
open The Harvest Moon.

713
00:42:29,172 --> 00:42:31,130
[PHONE RINGS]

714
00:42:31,131 --> 00:42:33,129
Maggie,

715
00:42:33,130 --> 00:42:34,881
we believe
in this project.

716
00:42:34,882 --> 00:42:38,213
We’re gonna give you
the extra 30,000 you need.

717
00:42:38,214 --> 00:42:40,214
Oh, no. It’s 50.
Thirty.

718
00:42:40,215 --> 00:42:42,130
Fifty!
Thirty, Maggie.

719
00:42:42,131 --> 00:42:44,254
John Fleming came
in with the new figures.

720
00:42:44,255 --> 00:42:48,130
He promised us he could do
the job, first class, for 30.

721
00:42:48,131 --> 00:42:50,713
Now, we trust John.

722
00:42:54,047 --> 00:42:56,130
You really are
the friendly bank.

723
00:42:57,504 --> 00:43:01,004
Okay, what’s the matter?

724
00:43:01,005 --> 00:43:02,462
Oh, that was a good sigh.

725
00:43:02,463 --> 00:43:04,880
You know, you can sigh
when you’re happy.

726
00:43:04,881 --> 00:43:07,047
You can even cry
when you’re happy.

727
00:43:07,048 --> 00:43:09,461
I’ve always thought
that was amazing.

728
00:43:09,462 --> 00:43:11,087
Come on,
let’s celebrate.

729
00:43:11,088 --> 00:43:13,171
No. Got work to do
for the next three days.

730
00:43:13,172 --> 00:43:15,421
We... We must
celebrate you.

731
00:43:15,422 --> 00:43:18,837
Maggie Patterson,
former teen waitress,

732
00:43:18,838 --> 00:43:20,629
and this amazing
accomplishment.

733
00:43:20,630 --> 00:43:24,544
Yes, it is, isn’t it?
Yes.

734
00:43:24,545 --> 00:43:27,378
I’m gonna send a copy
of this deed to my ex.

735
00:43:27,379 --> 00:43:31,878
All right. To, um,
anger, revenge, spite.

736
00:43:31,879 --> 00:43:33,128
No.
What?

737
00:43:33,129 --> 00:43:36,003
To love.

738
00:43:36,004 --> 00:43:38,545
That other stuff’s good
for a while, but it buries you.

739
00:43:38,546 --> 00:43:40,753
It makes you ugly.
All right.

740
00:43:40,754 --> 00:43:42,003
To love.
To love.

